<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM28400 - Approval of SIPs: Plan rules relating to alterations</h1>
<p>The SIP Code does not provide for an automatic loss of approval in the event that an alteration is made to the plan that would not be capable of approval.  This would, however, constitute a “disqualifying event” and approval may be withdrawn under paragraph 83 (2). </p>
<p>The normal procedure to be followed is for proposed alterations to be submitted to ESSU for review and if capable of approval then an approval letter is issued in a standard format advising that the approval of the alterations will come into effect on the date that they are adopted by the company. If the alterations have already been adopted by the company then the alterations will be approved from the date of the HMRC letter approving such amendments. </p>
<p>ESSU require companies, where appropriate, to provide in their plan rules that no amendment to a “key feature” of the plan shall take effect until it has been approved by HM Revenue and Customs.</p>
<p>An exception is that, in operating such rules, resolutions may express alterations</p>
<ul>
<li>to be subject to HMRC approval being received, or </li>
<li>not to take effect until approved by HMRC, </li>
</ul>
<p>so that the date on which HMRC approval is given is the date that the alteration takes effect.</p>
<p>Where an amendment is made subject to conditions and these conditions are never met e.g. HMRC approval, then the amendment will never come into effect. If an amendment never comes into effect then this would not constitute a disqualifying event.</p>
<p>SIPs may be approved which provide that no amendment shall take effect unless approved by HMRC, although they can also cause practical difficulties. In particular, practical difficulties may arise because, in the interval between the making of the amendment and HMRC approval to it being given or refused, it will not be known what the effective plan rules are.</p>
<p>Before accepting SIPs containing “unless” provisions, scheme advisers</p>
<ul>
<li>should ensure that the company is aware of the practical difficulties, </li>
<li>should require the scheme rules to provide that HMRC is notified immediately amendments are made.</li>
</ul>
<p>If resolutions make amendments which are expressed not to take effect unless approved by HM Revenue and Customs and HMRC approval is subsequently given to such an amendment, the date from which it takes effect is the earlier date on which it was made by the passing of the relevant resolution.</p>
<p>If HMRC approval is never given to such an amendment, it never becomes effective.</p>
